{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"2abcb9c3-a94c-4a52-a7e5-1eb28028bfc9","content":"The migration is straightforward. In your project file, simply **remove** (or set to `false`) the `<UseVSTest>` property:\n\n```xml\n<Project Sdk=\"MSTest.Sdk/3.8.0\">\n  <PropertyGroup>\n    <!-- Remove this line (or set to false): -->\n    <!-- <UseVSTest>true</UseVSTest> -->\n  </PropertyGroup>\n</Project>\n```\n\n**What this does:**\n\n- MSTest.Sdk 3.8.0 uses Microsoft.Testing.Platform **by default**. Setting `UseVSTest` to `true` was opting out of it.\n- Removing that property (or setting it to `false`) switches you to the new platform runner.\n\n**Other things to be aware of:**\n\n1. **CLI usage changes** — run tests with `dotnet test` as before, but you can also run the test executable directly (`./YourTests.exe`).\n2. **VSTest-specific adapters** — if you rely on custom VSTest adapters/extensions, verify they have Microsoft.Testing.Platform equivalents.\n3. **CI/reporting** — the new platform produces `.trx` output via `--results-directory`, but flags differ slightly (e.g., `--report-trx`). Update CI scripts if needed.\n4. **`runsettings`** — still supported, but some platform-specific settings may need adjustment.\n\nNo other NuGet package changes are required when using the SDK-style project — the SDK handles the dependency wiring for you.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"380be448-dbfe-40c0-8cd9-3fd2e3d6d7ce","outputTokens":359,"requestId":"BC2C:4B044:1B479ED:1E5E29D:69FA9095"},"id":"3d8b79b6-2036-457c-89b6-697647db6e43","timestamp":"2026-05-06T00:51:43.261Z","parentId":"b4a9682c-476f-4454-b43e-6250d7ab28ae"}
